{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"104a73c2-26bb-424f-9cac-a851c9c7fad1","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these locations:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** (most likely):\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_<date>_<host>.ips`. Open with any text editor.\n\n2. **Console.app** — Launch it and check **Crash Reports** in the sidebar.\n\n3. **Core dumps** (if enabled):\n   ```bash\n   # Check/enable core dumps\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   # Cores typically land in /cores/\n   ls /cores/\n   ```\n   Core dumps are disabled by default on macOS. You must set `ulimit -c unlimited` **before** running the app.\n\n**Tip:** The `.ips` crash report in `DiagnosticReports` is usually sufficient — it includes the stack trace, signal info, and loaded libraries. No special setup is required; macOS generates it automatically on crash.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"99595776-8405-4c97-92e0-8fd46f42d3e9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":293,"requestId":"2057:3F23E5:720BDA:8475A7:69F01195"},"id":"ed4f25f1-0706-40e9-8fbf-bcf707212d62","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:47:09.812Z","parentId":"f9d9b4e6-80ab-4c84-b86c-322a8bbcda78"}
